# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1891-boston-reds-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1883-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1883 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 66–32 record and won the championship of the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1884 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 75–32 record, first place in the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] After the season, they played the National League champion Providence Grays in the 1884 World Series and lost three games to zero.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's fourth season in St.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and the fourth season in the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 79–33 during the season, best in the American Association, and won their first AA pennant.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] In the World Series, the Browns played the National League champion Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The series ended in dispute, with each club winning 3 games with 1 tie.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Manager Charlie Comiskey finally was able to assemble and direct a team from start to finish the way he wanted.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The team was built on daring baserunning, clutch hitting, and the best pitching in the league.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The team as a whole led the league in both earned run average (ERA) and overall runs allowed by a healthy margin over second-best Louisville.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Individually, Dave Foutz was outstanding, as he won 33 of the 46 games he started and ranked fifth in ERA.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] His teammate Bob Caruthers was even better, compiling league-leading totals in wins (40), ERA (2.07) and winning percentage (a stellar .755).
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns took over first place to stay in the second week of May, but they made a joke of the race in July.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] On successive home stands, they had winning streaks of 17 and 12 games, combining for a major-league record 27-game winning streak at home that still stands as the best ever.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] They finished games laps ahead of the second-place Cincinnati Red Stockings and earned a berth in the World Series against the National League champion Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1886-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's fifth season in St.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1886-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and the fifth season in the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1886-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 93–46 during the season and finished first in the American Association, winning their second pennant in a row.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1886-st-louis-browns-season] In the World Series the Browns played the National League champion Chicago White Stockings, winning the series 4 games to 2.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1886-st-louis-browns-season] This was the only win by the AA in seven postseason contests with the NL from 1884 to 1890.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's sixth season in St.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and the sixth season in the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 95–40 during the season and finished first in the American Association, winning their third pennant in a row.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The team amassed 581 stolen bases, the most for any team whose records are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] In a postseason series (now referred to as the 1887 World Series), the Browns played the National League champion Detroit Wolverines, losing the series 10 games to 5.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Racial segregation started to become a custom in baseball about the time that eight members of the Browns withdrew from playing exhibition game in September against the Cuban Giants, a prominent 'colored' team.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] During this time, it was a popular practice to refer to teams of African American players as Cuban, Hispanic, or Arabian to deflect the racial stigma of the time, even though many were predominantly none of the three.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] News accounts reported that "for the first time in the history of base ball the color line has been drawn, and that by the St.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns were in Philadelphia with plans to travel to New York City to play the Cuban Giants in an exhibition game.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Scheduled long in advance with a "big guarantee", a crowd was anticipated in excess of 15,000 spectators.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] However, the night before departure to New York, eight Browns players signed a letter addressed to owner Chris von der Ahe and delivered it in person.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The letter was signed by eight players: Arlie Latham, Jack Boyle, Tip O'Neill, Bob Caruthers, Bill Gleason, Yank Robinson, Silver King, and Curt Welch.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Manager and first baseman Charlie Comiskey was reportedly unaware of the letter and Ed Knouff refused to sign it.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The Cuban Giants had previously played numerous exhibition games against other 'white' teams including Chicago, Indianapolis, Detroit, Louisville, Philadelphia.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] This was the first reported account that any club refused to play them because of their race.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The cancellation of the game with the Cuban Giants was merely symptomatic of a larger trend occurring in professional baseball.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] The boycott occurred during the same season in which Cap Anson of the Chicago White Stockings threatened not to play any 'white' professional teams who hired black players and just months after the International League prohibited further signing of black players.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Clearly the tide was moving toward segregation in baseball, so the St.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns' withdrawal brought wider attention to what was to become a norm in the United States.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1887-st-louis-browns-season] Ironically, it would be by an act 60 years later by then-former Cardinals executive in Branch Rickey that broke the color barrier in MLB when he débuted Jackie Robinson in 1947 with the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1888-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's seventh season in St.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1888-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and its seventh season in the American Association.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1888-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 92–43 during the season and finished first in the American Association, claiming their fourth pennant in a row.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1888-st-louis-browns-season] In the 1888 World Series, the Browns faced the National League champion New York Giants, losing the series 6 games to 4.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1891-boston-reds-season] The **1891 Boston Reds** baseball team finished the season with a 93–42 record and won the American Association championship in their first season in the new league after the demise of the Players' League.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1891-boston-reds-season] Thus they became only the second team (after the 1889–1890 Brooklyn Bridegrooms) to win championships in two different leagues in successive seasons, as well as the only team to win the pennant every single season of its existence.
[src:1891-boston-reds-season/1891-boston-reds-season] After the season, the AA also disbanded, and the Reds team folded with the league.
